	The aggregate market value of the 6,413,607 shares of common stock held by non-affiliates of the registrant, based on the closing sale price of the registrant&#8217;s common stock on June 30, 2015 of $4.81 per share was $30,849,450.
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: CENTER; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
	(APPLICABLE ONLY TO CORPORATE REGISTRANTS)
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; TEXT-INDENT: 18PT; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
	Indicate the number of shares outstanding for each of the registrant&#8217;s classes of common stock, as of the latest practicable date.
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; TEXT-INDENT: 18PT; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
	As of March 1, 2016, there were issued and outstanding 10,088,879 shares of the registrant&#8217;s common stock.
</DIV>

<TD STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: LEFT; WIDTH: AUTO; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT; VERTICAL-ALIGN: TOP">
	Bancorp&#8217;s ability to maintain effective internal controls over financial reporting and disclosure controls and procedures; and
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
</DIV>
<DIV>

</DIV>

<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: CENTER; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-WEIGHT: BOLD">
<U>
	PART I
</U>
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>
<EFX_BUSINESS>
<A NAME="FIS_BUSINESS"></A>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-WEIGHT: BOLD">
<U>
<A NAME="FORM10K_HTM_ITEM1">
<!--ANCHOR-->
</A>
	Item 1.&#160; Business
</U>
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: LEFT; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-WEIGHT: BOLD">
<U>
	General
</U>
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; TEXT-INDENT: 18PT; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
	Bancorp is a savings and loan holding company chartered as a corporation in the state of Maryland in 1990.&#160; It conducts business primarily through two subsidiaries, Severn Savings Bank, FSB (&#8220;Bank&#8221;) and SBI Mortgage Company (&#8220;SBI&#8221;).&#160; The Bank&#8217;s principal subsidiary Louis Hyatt, Inc. (&#8220;Hyatt Commercial&#8221;), conducts business as Hyatt Commercial, a commercial real estate brokerage and property management company.&#160; SBI holds mortgages that do not meet the underwriting criteria of the Bank, and is the parent company of Crownsville Development Corporation (&#8220;Crownsville&#8221;), which is doing business as Annapolis Equity Group, which acquires real estate for syndication and investment purposes.
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; TEXT-INDENT: 18PT; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
	The Bank has four branches in Anne Arundel County, Maryland, which offer a full range of deposit products, and originate mortgages in its primary market of Anne Arundel County, Maryland and, to a lesser extent, in other parts of Maryland, Delaware and Virginia.
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; TEXT-INDENT: 18PT; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
	On November 23, 2009, Bancorp and the Bank each entered into a supervisory agreement with the Office of Thrift Supervision (&#8220;OTS&#8221;).&#160; As a result of the Dodd-Frank Wall Street Reform and Consumer Protection Act (the &#8220;Dodd-Frank Act&#8221;), effective as of July 21, 2011, the OTS was abolished and the regulatory oversight functions and authority of the OTS related to the Bank were transferred to the Office of the Comptroller of the Currency (&#8220;OCC&#8221;) and the regulatory oversight functions and authority of the OTS related to Bancorp were transferred to the Board of Governors of the Federal Reserve System (&#8220;Federal Reserve&#8221; or &#8220;FRB&#8221;).&#160; The Bank&#8217;s supervisory agreement was replaced by a formal agreement dated April 13, 2013 with the OCC.&#160; On October 15, 2015, the Bank was notified by the OCC that its agreement was terminated.&#160; Bancorp&#8217;s supervisory agreement was enforced by FRB.&#160; On January 21, 2016, Bancorp was notified by the FRB that its agreement was terminated.
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; TEXT-INDENT: 18PT; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
	On April 23, 2013, the Bank was notified by the OCC that the OCC established minimum capital ratios for the Bank requiring it to immediately maintain a Tier I Leverage Capital Ratio to Adjusted Total Assets of at least 10% and a Total Risk-Based Capital to Risk-Weighted Assets ratio of at least 15%.&#160; On October 15, 2015, the Bank was notified by the OCC that these additional minimum capital ratios were no longer required.
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; TEXT-INDENT: 18PT; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
	As of December 31, 2015, Bancorp had total assets of $762,079,000, total deposits of $523,771,000, and total stockholders&#8217; equity of $86,456,000. Bancorp&#8217;s net income for the year ended December 31, 2015 was $4,535,000.&#160; For more information, see &#8220;Item 6. Selected Financial Data.&#8221;
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; TEXT-INDENT: 18PT; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
	Bancorp&#8217;s internet address is www.severnbank.com.&#160; Bancorp makes available free of charge on www.severnbank.com its annual report on Form 10-K, quarterly reports on Form 10-Q and current reports on Form 8-K, and amendments to those reports filed or furnished pursuant to Section 13(a) or 15(d) of the Exchange Act, as soon as reasonably practicable after it electronically files such material with, or furnishes it to, the SEC.
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; TEXT-INDENT: 18PT; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
	In addition, we will provide, at no cost, paper or electronic copies of our reports and other filings made with the SEC.&#160; Requests should be directed to:
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: CENTER; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
	Thomas G. Bevivino
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: CENTER; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
	Executive Vice President
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: CENTER; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
	Severn Bancorp, Inc.
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: CENTER; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
	200 Westgate Circle, Suite 200
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: CENTER; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
	Annapolis, Maryland 21401
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; TEXT-INDENT: 18PT; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
	The information on the website listed above, is not and should not be considered part of this Annual Report on Form 10-K and is not incorporated by reference in this document.&#160; This website is and is only intended to be an inactive textual reference.
</DIV>

	&#160;

<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: CENTER" ID="DSPFPAGENUMBERAREA">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-STYLE: NORMAL; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 8PT; FONT-WEIGHT: NORMAL" ID="DSPFPAGENUMBER">
	1
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="PAGE-BREAK-AFTER: ALWAYS" ID="DSPFPAGEBREAK">
<HR STYLE="BORDER-RIGHT-WIDTH: 0PX; BACKGROUND-COLOR: #000000; MARGIN: 4PX 0PX; WIDTH: 100%; BORDER-TOP-WIDTH: 0PX; BORDER-BOTTOM-WIDTH: 0PX; HEIGHT: 2PX; COLOR: #000000; CLEAR: BOTH; BORDER-LEFT-WIDTH: 0PX" NOSHADE="NOSHADE">
</DIV>
<A NAME="eolPage7"></A>
<DIV STYLE="WIDTH: 100%" ID="DSPFPAGEHEADER">
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: LEFT; FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL; FONT-STYLE: ITALIC; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 8PT; FONT-WEIGHT: NORMAL">
<A HREF="#FORM10K_HTM_TABLEOFCONTENTS">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</DIV>
</DIV>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-WEIGHT: BOLD">
<U>
	Business of the Bank
</U>
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; TEXT-INDENT: 18PT; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
	The Bank was organized in 1946 in Baltimore, Maryland as Pompei Permanent Building and Loan Association.&#160; It relocated to Annapolis, Maryland in 1980 and its name was changed to Severn Savings Association.&#160; Subsequently, the Bank obtained a federal charter and changed its name to Severn Savings Bank, FSB.&#160; The Bank operates four full-service branch offices and one administrative office.&#160; The Bank operates as a federally chartered savings bank whose principal business is attracting deposits from the general public and investing those funds in mortgage and commercial loans.&#160;&#160; The Bank also uses advances, or loans, from the Federal Home Loan Bank of Atlanta, (&#8220;FHLB-Atlanta&#8221;) to fund its lending activities.&#160; The Bank provides a wide range of personal and commercial banking services. Personal services include mortgage lending and various other lending services as well as checking, savings, money market, time deposit and individual retirement accounts. Commercial services include commercial secured and unsecured lending services as well as business internet banking, corporate cash management services and deposit services.&#160; The Bank also provides safe deposit boxes, ATMs, debit cards, and personal internet banking including on-line bill pay, mortgage lending, and telephone banking, among other products and services.
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; TEXT-INDENT: 18PT; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
	The Bank&#8217;s revenues are derived principally from interest earned on mortgage, commercial and other loans, and fees charged in connection with the loans and banking services.&#160; The Bank&#8217;s primary sources of funds are deposits, advances from the FHLB-Atlanta, proceeds from loans sold on the secondary market, and payments and principal prepayment of its loans.&#160; The principal executive offices of the Bank are maintained at 200 Westgate Circle, Suite 200, Annapolis Maryland, 21401.&#160; Its telephone number is 410-260-2000 and its e-mail address is
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<U>
	mailman@severnbank.com.
</U>
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV>
	&#160;
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-WEIGHT: BOLD">
<U>
	The Thrift Industry
</U>
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; TEXT-INDENT: 18PT; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
	Thrift institutions are financial intermediaries which historically have accepted savings deposits from the general public and, to a lesser extent, borrowed funds from outside sources and invested those deposits and funds primarily in loans secured by first mortgage liens on residential and other types of real estate.&#160; Such institutions may also invest their funds in various types of short- and long-term securities.&#160; The deposits of bank and thrift institutions are insured by the Deposit Insurance Fund (&#8220;DIF&#8221;) as administered by the Federal Deposit Insurance Corporation (&#8220;FDIC&#8221;), and these institutions are subject to extensive regulations.&#160; These regulations govern, among other things, the lending and other investment powers of thrift institutions, including the terms of mortgage instruments these institutions are permitted to utilize, the types of deposits they are permitted to accept, and reserve requirements.
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; TEXT-INDENT: 18PT; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
	The operations of thrift institutions, including those of the Bank, are significantly affected by general economic conditions and by related monetary and fiscal policies of the federal government and regulations and policies of financial institution regulatory authorities, including the Federal Reserve and the OCC into which the former OTS was merged.&#160; Lending activities are influenced by a number of factors including the demand for housing, conditions in the construction industry, and availability of funds.&#160; Sources of funds for lending activities include savings deposits, loan principal payments, proceeds from sales of loans, borrowings from the FHLB-Atlanta and other sources.&#160; Savings flows at thrift institutions such as the Bank are influenced by a number of factors including interest rates on competing investments and levels of personal income.
</DIV>
<DIV>
	&#160;
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="MARGIN-TOP: 10PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM: 10PT; CLEAR: BOTH" ID="DSPFPAGEBREAKAREA">
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: CENTER" ID="DSPFPAGENUMBERAREA">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-STYLE: NORMAL; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 8PT; FONT-WEIGHT: NORMAL" ID="DSPFPAGENUMBER">
	2
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="PAGE-BREAK-AFTER: ALWAYS" ID="DSPFPAGEBREAK">
<HR STYLE="BORDER-RIGHT-WIDTH: 0PX; BACKGROUND-COLOR: #000000; MARGIN: 4PX 0PX; WIDTH: 100%; BORDER-TOP-WIDTH: 0PX; BORDER-BOTTOM-WIDTH: 0PX; HEIGHT: 2PX; COLOR: #000000; CLEAR: BOTH; BORDER-LEFT-WIDTH: 0PX" NOSHADE="NOSHADE">
</DIV>
<A NAME="eolPage8"></A>
<DIV STYLE="WIDTH: 100%" ID="DSPFPAGEHEADER">
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: LEFT; FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL; FONT-STYLE: ITALIC; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 8PT; FONT-WEIGHT: NORMAL">
<A HREF="#FORM10K_HTM_TABLEOFCONTENTS">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</DIV>
</DIV>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-WEIGHT: BOLD">
<U>
	Earnings
</U>
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; TEXT-INDENT: 18PT; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
	The Bank&#8217;s earnings depend primarily on the difference between income from interest-earning assets such as loans and investments, and interest paid on interest-bearing liabilities such as deposits and borrowings.&#160; The Bank typically engages in long-term mortgage lending at fixed rates of interest, generally for periods of up to 30 years, while accepting deposits for considerably shorter periods.&#160; However, many of the Bank&#8217;s long-term fixed-rate loans are sold in the secondary market, typically resulting in net gains on the sale of such loans by the Bank.
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; TEXT-INDENT: 18PT; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
	Generally, rapidly rising interest rates cause the cost of interest-bearing liabilities to increase more rapidly than yields on interest-earning assets, thereby adversely affecting the earnings of many thrift institutions.&#160; While the industry has received expanded lending and borrowing powers in recent years permitting different types of investments and mortgage loans, including those with floating or adjustable rates and those with shorter terms, earnings and operations are still highly influenced by levels of interest rates and financial market conditions and by substantial investments in long-term mortgage loans.
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-WEIGHT: BOLD">
<U>
	Competition
</U>
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; TEXT-INDENT: 18PT; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
	The Annapolis, Maryland area has a high density of financial institutions, many of which are significantly larger and have greater financial resources than the Bank, and all of which are competitors of the Bank to varying degrees.&#160; The Bank&#8217;s competition for loans comes primarily from savings and loan associations, savings banks, mortgage banking companies, insurance companies, and commercial banks.&#160; Many of the Bank&#8217;s competitors have higher legal lending limits than the Bank.&#160; The Bank&#8217;s most direct competition for deposits has historically come from savings and loan associations, savings banks, commercial banks, and credit unions.&#160; The Bank faces additional competition for deposits from short-term money market funds and other corporate and government securities funds.&#160; The Bank also faces increased competition for deposits from other financial institutions such as brokerage firms, insurance companies and mutual funds.&#160; The Bank is a community-oriented financial institution serving its market area with a wide selection of mortgage loans.&#160; Management considers the Bank&#8217;s reputation for financial strength and customer service as its major competitive advantage in attracting and retaining customers in its market area.&#160; The Bank also believes it benefits from its community orientation.
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-WEIGHT: BOLD">
<U>
	Net Interest Income
</U>
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; TEXT-INDENT: 18PT; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
	Net interest income increases during periods when the spread between Bancorp&#8217;s weighted average rate at which new loans are originated and the weighted average cost of interest-bearing liabilities widens.&#160; Market factors such as interest rates, competition, consumer preferences, the supply of and demand for housing, and the availability of funds affect the Bank&#8217;s ability to originate loans.
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; TEXT-INDENT: 18PT; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
	Bancorp has supplemented its interest income through purchases of investments when appropriate.&#160; This activity is intended to generate positive interest rate spreads on large principal balances with minimal administrative expense.
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-WEIGHT: BOLD">
<U>
	Interest Rate and Volume of Interest-Related Assets and Liabilities
</U>
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; TEXT-INDENT: 18PT; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
	Both changes in rate and changes in the composition of Bancorp&#8217;s interest-earning assets and interest-bearing liabilities can have a significant effect on net interest income.
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; TEXT-INDENT: 18PT; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
	For information concerning the extent to which changes in interest rates and changes in volume of interest-related assets and liabilities have affected Bancorp&#8217;s interest income and expense during the fiscal years ended December 31, 2015 and 2014, refer to Item 6, &#8220;Selected Financial Data - Rate Volume Table&#8221;.
</DIV>
<DIV>
	&#160;
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="MARGIN-TOP: 10PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM: 10PT; CLEAR: BOTH" ID="DSPFPAGEBREAKAREA">
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: CENTER" ID="DSPFPAGENUMBERAREA">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-STYLE: NORMAL; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 8PT; FONT-WEIGHT: NORMAL" ID="DSPFPAGENUMBER">
	3
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="PAGE-BREAK-AFTER: ALWAYS" ID="DSPFPAGEBREAK">
<HR STYLE="BORDER-RIGHT-WIDTH: 0PX; BACKGROUND-COLOR: #000000; MARGIN: 4PX 0PX; WIDTH: 100%; BORDER-TOP-WIDTH: 0PX; BORDER-BOTTOM-WIDTH: 0PX; HEIGHT: 2PX; COLOR: #000000; CLEAR: BOTH; BORDER-LEFT-WIDTH: 0PX" NOSHADE="NOSHADE">
</DIV>
<A NAME="eolPage9"></A>
<DIV STYLE="WIDTH: 100%" ID="DSPFPAGEHEADER">
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: LEFT; FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL; FONT-STYLE: ITALIC; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 8PT; FONT-WEIGHT: NORMAL">
<A HREF="#FORM10K_HTM_TABLEOFCONTENTS">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</DIV>
</DIV>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-WEIGHT: BOLD">
<U>
	Market Area
</U>
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; TEXT-INDENT: 18PT; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
	The Bank&#8217;s market area is primarily Anne Arundel County, Maryland and nearby areas, due to its four branch locations, all being located in Anne Arundel County.
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; TEXT-INDENT: 18PT; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
	The Bank continues to expand its business relationship banking department by focusing on the needs of the business community in Anne Arundel County, Maryland.&#160; In addition, the Bank increased its offerings to businesses and consumers, including additional commercial lending products, business internet banking, and an expanded line of consumer deposit products.&#160; The Bank has traditionally focused its lending activities on first mortgage loans secured by real estate for the purpose of purchasing, refinancing, developing and constructing one-to-four family residences and commercial properties in and near Anne Arundel County, Maryland. The demand for first mortgage lending has increased in 2015, as the Bank continues to be a leading mortgage lender in its market area in 2015.&#160; The Bank participates in the secondary market and sells loans it originates either with mortgage servicing rights released or retained.
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: LEFT; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-WEIGHT: BOLD">
<U>
	Supervisory and Formal Agreements
</U>
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; MARGIN-LEFT: 18PT; FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
	On November 23, 2009, Bancorp and the Bank each entered into a supervisory agreement with the OTS.
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; TEXT-INDENT: 18PT; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
	Bancorp&#8217;s agreement generally prohibited Bancorp from paying dividends or distributions, or incurring debt, without the prior approval of the FRB.&#160; As a result of the Dodd-Frank Act, Bancorp&#8217;s supervisory agreement was enforced by the FRB.&#160; However, on January 21, 2016, Bancorp was notified by the FRB that its supervisory agreement was terminated.
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY">
<BR>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; TEXT-INDENT: 18PT; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
	The Bank&#8217;s supervisory agreement was replaced by a formal agreement dated April 23, 2013 with the OCC.&#160; The formal agreement primarily addressed issues identified in the OCC&#8217;s report and examination of the Bank&#8217;s operations and financial condition in 2012 and prescribed certain corrective actions that the Bank must take.&#160; Additionally, on April 23, 2013, the Bank was notified by the OCC that the OCC established certain individual minimum capital ratios for the Bank. However, on October 15, 2015, the Bank was notified by the OCC that its formal agreement was terminated and that the additional minimum capital ratios were no longer required.
</DIV>
<DIV>
	&#160;
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="MARGIN-TOP: 10PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM: 10PT; CLEAR: BOTH" ID="DSPFPAGEBREAKAREA">
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: CENTER" ID="DSPFPAGENUMBERAREA">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-STYLE: NORMAL; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 8PT; FONT-WEIGHT: NORMAL" ID="DSPFPAGENUMBER">
	4

<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-WEIGHT: BOLD">

<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT">

<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-WEIGHT: BOLD">
<U>
	Lending Activities
</U>
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; MARGIN-LEFT: 18PT; FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-WEIGHT: BOLD">
<U>
	General
</U>
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; TEXT-INDENT: 18PT; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
	The Bank originates mortgage loans of all types, including residential, residential-construction, commercial-construction, commercial, land and residential lot loans.&#160; The Bank also originates non-mortgage loans, which include consumer, business and commercial loans.&#160; These loans constitute a small part of the Bank&#8217;s portfolio.
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; MARGIN-LEFT: 18PT; FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
	The Bank originated and funded $282,828,000 and $232,781,000 of loans for the years ended December 31, 2015 and 2014, respectively.
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>

<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; TEXT-INDENT: 18PT; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
	The Bank originates residential mortgage loans that are to be held in the Bank&#8217;s loan portfolio as well as loans that are intended for sale in the secondary market.&#160; Loans sold in the secondary market are primarily sold to investors with which the Bank maintains a correspondent relationship.&#160; These loans are made in conformity with standard underwriting criteria to assure maximum eligibility for possible resale in the secondary market, and are approved either by the Bank&#8217;s underwriter or the correspondent&#8217;s underwriter.&#160; Loans considered for the Bank&#8217;s portfolio with borrowers that have lending relationships less than $500,000 are approved by any of the Bank&#8217;s Officers, which includes the Chief Executive Officer, the Chief Operating Officer, the Chief Financial Officer, the Chief Credit Officer and the Chief Lending Officer.&#160; Loans considered for the Bank&#8217;s portfolio with borrowers that have lending relationships of $500,000 or greater are approved by the Bank&#8217;s Directors Loan Committee.&#160; Meetings of the Directors Loan Committee are open to attendance by any member of the Bank&#8217;s Board of Directors who wishes to attend.&#160; The loan committee reports to and consults with the Board of Directors in interpreting and applying the Bank&#8217;s lending policy.&#160; Single loans greater than $2,000,000, or loans to one borrower aggregating more than $4,000,000, up to $16,944,000 (the maximum amount of loans to one borrower as of December 31, 2015), must also have Board of Directors&#8217; approval.
</DIV>
<DIV>
	&#160;
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="MARGIN-TOP: 10PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM: 10PT; CLEAR: BOTH" ID="DSPFPAGEBREAKAREA">

<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; TEXT-INDENT: 18PT; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
	Loans that are sold are typically long-term (15 or more years) loans with fixed interest rates eligible for resale in the secondary market.&#160; Loans retained for Bancorp&#8217;s portfolio typically include construction loans, commercial loans and loans that periodically reprice or mature prior to the end of an amortized term.&#160; Loans are sold with either servicing released or retained by the Bank.&#160; As of December 31, 2015, the Bank was servicing $20,454,000 in loans for Federal Home Loan Mortgage Corporation (&#8220;FHLMC&#8221;), $44,366,000 in loans for Federal National Mortgage Association (&#8220;FNMA&#8221;) and $11,640,000 in loans for other investors.
</DIV>

<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; TEXT-INDENT: 18PT; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
	The Bank&#8217;s mortgage loan approval process is intended to assess the borrower&#8217;s ability to repay the loan, the viability of the loan, and the adequacy of the value of the property that will secure the loan.&#160; The authority of the Directors Loan Committee to approve loans is established by the Board of Directors and currently is commensurate with the Bank&#8217;s limitation on loans to one borrower.&#160; The Bank&#8217;s maximum amount of loans to one borrower currently is equal to 15% of the Bank&#8217;s unimpaired capital, or $16,944,000 as of December 31, 2015.&#160; Loans greater than this amount require participation by one or more additional lenders.&#160; Letters of credit are subject to the same limitations as direct loans.&#160; The Bank utilizes independent qualified appraisers approved by the Board of Directors to appraise the properties securing its loans and requires title insurance or title opinions so as to insure that the Bank has a valid lien on the mortgaged real estate.&#160; The Bank requires borrowers to maintain fire and casualty insurance on its secured properties.
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; TEXT-INDENT: 18PT; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
	The procedure for approval of construction loans is the same for residential mortgage loans, except that the appraiser evaluates the building plans, construction specifications, and estimates of construction costs.&#160; The Bank also evaluates the feasibility of the proposed construction project and the experience and track record of the developer.&#160; In addition, all construction loans generally require a commitment from a third-party lender or from the Bank for a permanent long-term loan to replace the construction loan upon completion of construction.
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-WEIGHT: BOLD">
<U>
	Residential Mortgage Loans
</U>
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; TEXT-INDENT: 18PT; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
	At December 31, 2015, Bancorp&#8217;s residential mortgage loan portfolio totaled $285,930,000, or 45.0% of Bancorp&#8217;s loan portfolio.&#160; All of Bancorp&#8217;s residential mortgage loans are secured by one to four family residential properties.
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-WEIGHT: BOLD">
<U>
	Commercial Real Estate Loans
</U>
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; TEXT-INDENT: 18PT; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
	At December 31, 2015, Bancorp&#8217;s commercial real estate loan portfolio totaled $174,912,000, or 27.5% of Bancorp&#8217;s loan portfolio.&#160; All of Bancorp&#8217;s commercial real estate loans are secured by improved property such as office buildings, retail strip shopping centers, industrial condominium units and other small businesses, most of which are located in the Bank&#8217;s primary lending area.&#160; The largest commercial real estate loan outstanding at December 31, 2015 was a $7,945,000 loan secured by a commercial property in Edgewater, Maryland.&#160; This loan has consistently performed in accordance with the terms of the debt instrument.
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; TEXT-INDENT: 18PT; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
	Loans secured by commercial real estate properties generally involve a greater degree of risk than residential mortgage loans.&#160; Because payments on loans secured by commercial real estate properties are often dependent on the successful operation or management of the properties, repayment of these loans may be subject to a greater extent to adverse conditions in the real estate market or the economy.
</DIV>
<DIV>
	&#160;
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="MARGIN-TOP: 10PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM: 10PT; CLEAR: BOTH" ID="DSPFPAGEBREAKAREA">
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: CENTER" ID="DSPFPAGENUMBERAREA">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-STYLE: NORMAL; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 8PT; FONT-WEIGHT: NORMAL" ID="DSPFPAGENUMBER">
	7
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="PAGE-BREAK-AFTER: ALWAYS" ID="DSPFPAGEBREAK">
<HR STYLE="BORDER-RIGHT-WIDTH: 0PX; BACKGROUND-COLOR: #000000; MARGIN: 4PX 0PX; WIDTH: 100%; BORDER-TOP-WIDTH: 0PX; BORDER-BOTTOM-WIDTH: 0PX; HEIGHT: 2PX; COLOR: #000000; CLEAR: BOTH; BORDER-LEFT-WIDTH: 0PX" NOSHADE="NOSHADE">
</DIV>
<A NAME="eolPage13"></A>
<DIV STYLE="WIDTH: 100%" ID="DSPFPAGEHEADER">
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: LEFT; FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL; FONT-STYLE: ITALIC; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 8PT; FONT-WEIGHT: NORMAL">
<A HREF="#FORM10K_HTM_TABLEOFCONTENTS">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</DIV>
</DIV>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-WEIGHT: BOLD">
<U>
	Construction and Land Acquisition and Development Loans
</U>
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; TEXT-INDENT: 18PT; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
	The Bank originates loans to finance the construction of one-to-four family dwellings, and to a lesser extent, commercial real estate.&#160; It also originates loans for the acquisition and development of unimproved property to be used for residential and/or commercial purposes in cases where the Bank is to provide the construction funds to improve the properties.&#160; As of December 31, 2015, Bancorp had 90 construction loans outstanding in the gross aggregate amount of $77,478,000, representing 12.2% of its loan portfolio.&#160; Included in that total were commitments to advance an additional $21,101,000.
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; TEXT-INDENT: 18PT; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
	Construction loan amounts are based on the appraised value of the property and, for builder loans, a feasibility study as to the potential marketability and profitability of the project.&#160; Construction loans generally have terms of up to one year, with reasonable extensions as needed, and typically have interest rates that float monthly at margins ranging from the prime rate to 2 percent above the prime rate.&#160;&#160; In addition to builders&#8217; projects, the Bank finances the construction of single family, owner-occupied houses where qualified contractors are involved and on the basis of strict written underwriting and construction loan guidelines.&#160; Construction loans are structured either to be converted to permanent loans with the Bank upon the expiration of the construction phase or to be paid off by financing from another financial institution.
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; TEXT-INDENT: 18PT; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
	Construction loans afford the Bank the opportunity to increase the interest rate sensitivity of its loan portfolio and to receive yields higher than those obtainable on loans secured by existing residential properties.&#160; These higher yields correspond to the higher risks associated with construction lending.&#160;&#160; Construction loans involve additional risks attributable to the fact that loan funds are advanced upon the security of the project under construction that is of uncertain value prior to its completion.&#160; Because of the uncertainties inherent in estimating construction costs as well as the market value of the completed project and the effects of governmental regulation of real property, it is relatively difficult to value accurately the total funds required to complete a project and the related loan-to-value ratio.&#160; As a result, construction lending often involves the disbursement of substantial funds with repayment dependent, in part, on the ultimate success of the project rather than the ability of the borrower or guarantor to repay principal and interest.&#160; If the Bank is forced to foreclose on a project prior to or at completion, due to a default, there can be no assurance that the Bank will be able to recover all of the unpaid balance of the loan as well as related foreclosure and holding costs.&#160; In addition, the Bank may be required to fund additional amounts to complete the project and may have to hold the property for an unspecified period of time.&#160; The Bank has attempted to address these risks through its underwriting procedures and its limited amount of construction lending on multi-family and commercial real estate properties.
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; TEXT-INDENT: 18PT; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
	It is the policy of the Bank to conduct physical inspections of each property secured by a construction or rehabilitation loan for the purpose of reporting upon the progress of the construction of improvements.&#160; These inspections, referred to as &#8220;construction draw inspections,&#8221; are to be performed at the time of a request for an advance of construction funds.&#160; If no construction advance has been requested, a construction inspector or senior officer of the institution makes an inspection of the subject property at least quarterly.
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-WEIGHT: BOLD">
<U>
	Land and Residential Building Lots
</U>
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; TEXT-INDENT: 18PT; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
	Land loans include loans to developers for the development of residential subdivisions and loans on unimproved lots primarily to individuals.&#160; At December 31, 2015, Bancorp had outstanding land and residential building lot loans totaling $28,677,000, or 4.5% of the total loan portfolio.&#160; The largest of these loans is for $4,800,000, is secured by residential lots in Severn, Maryland, and has performed in accordance with the terms of the debt instrument.&#160; Land development loans typically are short-term loans; the duration of these loans is typically not greater than three years.&#160; The interest rate on land loans is generally at least 1% or 2% over the prime rate.&#160;&#160; The loan-to-value ratio generally does not exceed 75% at the time of loan origination. Land and residential building lot loans typically are made to customers of the Bank and developers and contractors with whom the Bank has had previous lending experience.&#160; In addition to the customary requirements for these types of loans, the Bank may also require a satisfactory Phase I environmental study and feasibility study to determine the profit potential of the development.
</DIV>
<DIV>
	&#160;
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="MARGIN-TOP: 10PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM: 10PT; CLEAR: BOTH" ID="DSPFPAGEBREAKAREA">
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: CENTER" ID="DSPFPAGENUMBERAREA">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-STYLE: NORMAL; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 8PT; FONT-WEIGHT: NORMAL" ID="DSPFPAGENUMBER">
	8
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="PAGE-BREAK-AFTER: ALWAYS" ID="DSPFPAGEBREAK">
<HR STYLE="BORDER-RIGHT-WIDTH: 0PX; BACKGROUND-COLOR: #000000; MARGIN: 4PX 0PX; WIDTH: 100%; BORDER-TOP-WIDTH: 0PX; BORDER-BOTTOM-WIDTH: 0PX; HEIGHT: 2PX; COLOR: #000000; CLEAR: BOTH; BORDER-LEFT-WIDTH: 0PX" NOSHADE="NOSHADE">
</DIV>
<A NAME="eolPage14"></A>
<DIV STYLE="WIDTH: 100%" ID="DSPFPAGEHEADER">
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: LEFT; FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL; FONT-STYLE: ITALIC; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 8PT; FONT-WEIGHT: NORMAL">
<A HREF="#FORM10K_HTM_TABLEOFCONTENTS">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</DIV>
</DIV>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-WEIGHT: BOLD">
<U>
	Lines of Credit and Commercial Non-Real Estate Loans
</U>
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; TEXT-INDENT: 18PT; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
	The Bank also offers other business and commercial loans.&#160; These are loans to businesses are typically lines of credit or other loans that are not secured by real estate, although equipment, securities, or other collateral may secure them.&#160; They typically are offered to customers with long-standing relationships with the Bank.&#160; At December 31, 2015, $29,484,000, or 4.6%, of the loan portfolio consisted of lines of credit and other commercial loans.
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-WEIGHT: BOLD">
<U>
	Home Equity and Other Consumer Loans
</U>
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; TEXT-INDENT: 18PT; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
	The Bank also offers other loans to consumers, including home equity loans, home equity lines of credit and other consumer loans.&#160; At December 31, 2015, $25,753,000, or 4.1% of the loan portfolio consisted of these loans.
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-WEIGHT: BOLD">
<U>
	Loan Portfolio Cash Flows
</U>
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; TEXT-INDENT: 18PT; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
	The following table sets forth the estimated maturity of Bancorp&#8217;s loan portfolios by type of loan at December 31, 2015.&#160; The estimated maturity reflects contractual terms at December 31, 2015.&#160; Contractual principal repayments of loans do not necessarily reflect the actual life of the Bank&#8217;s loan portfolios.&#160; The average life of mortgage loans is substantially less than their contractual terms because of loan prepayments and because of enforcement of &#8220;due on sale&#8221; clauses.&#160; The average life of mortgage loans tends to increase, however, when current mortgage loan rates substantially exceed rates on existing mortgage loans.
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>

</DIV>
</TD>
<TD STYLE="BORDER-BOTTOM: #000000 4PX DOUBLE; TEXT-ALIGN: RIGHT; BACKGROUND-COLOR: #CCEEFF; WIDTH: 9%; VERTICAL-ALIGN: BOTTOM" VALIGN="BOTTOM">
<DIV STYLE="FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
	508,830
</DIV>
</TD>
<TD STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: LEFT; PADDING-BOTTOM: 4PX; BACKGROUND-COLOR: #CCEEFF; WIDTH: 1%; VERTICAL-ALIGN: BOTTOM" VALIGN="BOTTOM" NOWRAP="NOWRAP">
	&#160;
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
</EFX_UNIDENTIFIED_TABLE>
<DIV>
	&#160;
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="MARGIN-LEFT: 27PT">
	*Includes loans categorized as held for sale.
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-WEIGHT: BOLD">
<U>
	Loans to One Borrower
</U>
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; TEXT-INDENT: 18PT; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
	Under regulatory guidelines, the aggregate amount of loans that the Bank may make to one borrower was $16,944,000 at December 31, 2015, which is 15% of the Bank&#8217;s unimpaired capital and unimpaired surplus.&#160; The Bank&#8217;s three largest loans at December 31, 2015 were a $7,945,000 loan secured by a commercial property located in Edgewater, Maryland, a $5,092,000 loan secured by commercial property in Columbia, Maryland and a $4,800,000 loan secured by residential property located in Severn, Maryland.&#160; All three loans are performing as agreed.
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY">
<BR>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-WEIGHT: BOLD">
<U>
	Origination and Purchase and Sale of Loans
</U>
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; TEXT-INDENT: 18PT; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
	The Bank originates residential loans in conformity with standard underwriting criteria to assure maximum eligibility for possible resale in the secondary market.&#160; Although the Bank has authority to lend anywhere in the United States, it has confined its loan origination activities primarily to the states of Maryland, Virginia and Delaware.
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; TEXT-INDENT: 18PT; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
	Loan originations are developed from a number of sources, primarily from referrals from real estate brokers, internet leads, builders, and existing and walk&#8209;in customers.
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; TEXT-INDENT: 18PT; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
	The Bank&#8217;s mortgage loan approval process is intended to assess the borrower's ability to repay the loan, the viability of the loan, and the adequacy of the value of the property that will secure the loan.&#160; Loans considered for the Bank&#8217;s portfolio with borrowers that have lending relationships less than $500,000 are approved by any of the Bank&#8217;s Officers, which includes the Chief Executive Officer, the Chief Operating Officer, the Chief Financial Officer, the Chief Credit Officer and the Chief Lending Officer.&#160; Loans considered for the Bank&#8217;s portfolio with borrowers that have lending relationships of $500,000 or greater are approved by the Bank&#8217;s Directors Loan Committee.&#160; Meetings of the Directors&#8217; Loan Committee are open to attendance by any member of the Bank&#8217;s Board of Directors who wishes to attend.&#160; The loan committee reports to and consults with the Board of Directors in interpreting and applying the Bank&#8217;s lending policy.&#160; Single loans greater than $2,000,000, or loans to one borrower aggregating more than $4,000,000, up to $16,944,000 (the maximum amount of loans to one borrower as of December 31, 2015), must also have Board of Directors&#8217; approval. The Bank utilizes independent qualified appraisers approved by the Board of Directors to appraise the properties securing its loans and requires title insurance or title opinions so as to insure that the Bank has a valid lien on the mortgaged real estate. The Bank requires borrowers to maintain fire and casualty insurance on its secured properties.
</DIV>
<DIV>
	&#160;
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="MARGIN-TOP: 10PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM: 10PT; CLEAR: BOTH" ID="DSPFPAGEBREAKAREA">
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: CENTER" ID="DSPFPAGENUMBERAREA">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-STYLE: NORMAL; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 8PT; FONT-WEIGHT: NORMAL" ID="DSPFPAGENUMBER">
	10
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="PAGE-BREAK-AFTER: ALWAYS" ID="DSPFPAGEBREAK">
<HR STYLE="BORDER-RIGHT-WIDTH: 0PX; BACKGROUND-COLOR: #000000; MARGIN: 4PX 0PX; WIDTH: 100%; BORDER-TOP-WIDTH: 0PX; BORDER-BOTTOM-WIDTH: 0PX; HEIGHT: 2PX; COLOR: #000000; CLEAR: BOTH; BORDER-LEFT-WIDTH: 0PX" NOSHADE="NOSHADE">
</DIV>
<A NAME="eolPage16"></A>
<DIV STYLE="WIDTH: 100%" ID="DSPFPAGEHEADER">
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: LEFT; FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL; FONT-STYLE: ITALIC; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 8PT; FONT-WEIGHT: NORMAL">
<A HREF="#FORM10K_HTM_TABLEOFCONTENTS">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</DIV>
</DIV>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; TEXT-INDENT: 18PT; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
	The procedure for approval of construction loans is the same as for residential mortgage loans, except that the appraiser evaluates the building plans, construction specifications, and estimates of construction costs.&#160; The Bank also evaluates the feasibility of the proposed construction project and the experience and track record of the developer.&#160; In addition, all construction loans generally require a commitment from a third-party lender or from the Bank for a permanent long-term loan to replace the construction loan upon completion of construction.
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; TEXT-INDENT: 18PT; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
	Consumer loans are underwritten on the basis of the borrower's credit history and an analysis of the borrower's income and expenses, ability to repay the loan, and the value of the collateral, if any.
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; TEXT-INDENT: 18PT; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
	Currently, it is the Bank&#8217;s policy to originate both fixed-rate and adjustable-rate loans. The Bank is currently active in the secondary market and sells a portion of its fixed-rate loans.
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: LEFT; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-WEIGHT: BOLD">
<U>
	Interest Rates, Points and Fees
</U>
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; TEXT-INDENT: 18PT; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
	The Bank realizes interest, point, and fee income from its lending activities.&#160; The Bank also realizes income from commitment fees for making commitments to originate loans, and from prepayment and late charges, loan fees, application fees, and fees for other miscellaneous services.
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; TEXT-INDENT: 18PT; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
	The Bank accounts for loan origination fees in accordance with standards set on the accounting for deferred costs and fees. These standards prohibit the immediate recognition of loan origination fees as revenues and require that such income (net of certain direct loan origination costs) for each loan be amortized, generally by the interest method, over the estimated life of the loan as an adjustment of yield.&#160; The Bank also realizes income from gains on sales of loans, and servicing released fees for loans sold with servicing released.
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-WEIGHT: BOLD">
<U>
	Delinquencies and Classified Assets and Allowance for Loan Losses
</U>
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-WEIGHT: BOLD">
	Delinquencies
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; TEXT-INDENT: 18PT; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
	The Board of Directors reviews delinquencies on all loans monthly.&#160; The Bancorp&#8217;s collection procedures include sending a past due notice to the borrower on the 17th day of nonpayment, making telephone contact with the borrower between 20 and 30 days after nonpayment, and sending a letter after the 30th day of nonpayment. A notice of intent to foreclose is generally sent between 60 and 90 days after delinquency.&#160; When the borrower is contacted, Bancorp attempts to obtain full payment of the past due amount.&#160; However, Bancorp generally will seek to reach agreement with the borrower on a payment plan to avoid foreclosure.
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-WEIGHT: BOLD">
	Allowance for Loan Losses
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; TEXT-INDENT: 18PT; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
	An allowance for loan losses is provided through charges to income in an amount that management believes will be adequate to absorb losses on existing loans that may become uncollectible, based on evaluations of the collectability of loans and prior loan loss experience.&#160; The evaluations take into consideration such factors as changes in the nature and volume of the loan portfolio, overall portfolio quality, review of specific problem loans, and current economic conditions that may affect the borrowers' ability to pay.&#160; Determining the amount of the allowance for loan losses requires the use of estimates and assumptions, which is permitted under generally accepted accounting principles. Actual results could differ significantly from those estimates.&#160; Management believes the allowance for losses on loans is adequate. While management uses available information to estimate losses on loans, future additions to the allowances may be necessary based on changes in economic conditions, particularly in the State of Maryland.&#160; In addition, various regulatory agencies, as an integral part of their examination process, periodically review the Bank's allowance for losses on loans.&#160; Such agencies may require the Bank to recognize additions to the allowance based on their judgments about information available to them at the time of their examination.
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; TEXT-INDENT: 18PT; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
	The allowance consists of specific and general components.&#160; The specific component relates to loans that are classified as impaired.&#160; When a real estate secured loan becomes impaired, a decision is made as to whether an updated certified appraisal of the real estate is necessary.&#160; This decision is based on various considerations, including the age of the most recent appraisal, the loan-to-value ratio based on the original appraisal and the condition of the property.&#160; Appraised values are discounted to arrive at the estimated selling price of the collateral, which is considered to be the estimated fair value.&#160; The discounts also include estimated costs to sell the property.
</DIV>
<DIV>
	&#160;
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="MARGIN-TOP: 10PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM: 10PT; CLEAR: BOTH" ID="DSPFPAGEBREAKAREA">
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: CENTER" ID="DSPFPAGENUMBERAREA">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-STYLE: NORMAL; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 8PT; FONT-WEIGHT: NORMAL" ID="DSPFPAGENUMBER">
	11
</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="PAGE-BREAK-AFTER: ALWAYS" ID="DSPFPAGEBREAK">
<HR STYLE="BORDER-RIGHT-WIDTH: 0PX; BACKGROUND-COLOR: #000000; MARGIN: 4PX 0PX; WIDTH: 100%; BORDER-TOP-WIDTH: 0PX; BORDER-BOTTOM-WIDTH: 0PX; HEIGHT: 2PX; COLOR: #000000; CLEAR: BOTH; BORDER-LEFT-WIDTH: 0PX" NOSHADE="NOSHADE">
</DIV>
<A NAME="eolPage17"></A>
<DIV STYLE="WIDTH: 100%" ID="DSPFPAGEHEADER">
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: LEFT; FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL; FONT-STYLE: ITALIC; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 8PT; FONT-WEIGHT: NORMAL">
<A HREF="#FORM10K_HTM_TABLEOFCONTENTS">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</DIV>
</DIV>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; TEXT-INDENT: 18PT; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
	For loans secured by non-real estate collateral, such as accounts receivable, inventory and equipment, estimated fair values are determined based on the borrower&#8217;s financial statements, inventory reports, accounts receivable aging or equipment appraisals or invoices.&#160; Indications of value from these sources are generally discounted based on the age of the financial information and the quality of the assets.
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; TEXT-INDENT: 18PT; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
	For such loans that are classified as impaired, an allowance is established when the current market value of the underlying collateral less its estimated disposal costs has not been finalized, but management determines that it is likely that the value is lower than the carrying value of that loan.&#160; Once the net collateral value has been determined, a charge-off is taken for the difference between the net collateral value and the carrying value of the loan. For loans that are not solely collateral dependent, an allowance is established when the present value of the expected future cash flows of the impaired loan is lower than the carrying value of that loan.&#160; The general component relates to loans that are classified as doubtful, substandard or special mention that are not considered impaired, as well as non-classified loans.&#160; The general reserve is based on historical loss experience adjusted for qualitative factors.&#160; These qualitative factors include:
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY">
<TABLE STYLE="WIDTH: 100%; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT" ID="301E52EDFAF44E43B9D311FC6BE8A159" CLASS="DSPFLISTTABLE" CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="0">

</TD>

<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY">

<TD STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; WIDTH: AUTO; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT; VERTICAL-ALIGN: TOP">

</TD>

</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY">
<TABLE STYLE="WIDTH: 100%; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT" ID="C521B23590A540A395604A24F71D31C8" CLASS="DSPFLISTTABLE" CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="0">

</TD>
</TR>

</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY">
<TABLE STYLE="WIDTH: 100%; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT" ID="12E83BE4095C422CB2EB3987B6D8D053" CLASS="DSPFLISTTABLE" CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="0">
<TR>
<TD STYLE="WIDTH: 108PT">
</TD>

<TD STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; WIDTH: AUTO; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT; VERTICAL-ALIGN: TOP">

</TD>
</TR>

</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY">
<TABLE STYLE="WIDTH: 100%; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT" ID="BD324BF99C174CD990DD4EEB0B90E8E9" CLASS="DSPFLISTTABLE" CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="0">
<TR>

	National and local economic trends and conditions; and
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY">
<TABLE STYLE="WIDTH: 100%; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT" ID="9E97C0573D984DAFA4C5574F4CDEBAE4" CLASS="DSPFLISTTABLE" CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="0">
<TR>
<TD STYLE="WIDTH: 108PT">
</TD>
<TD STYLE="WIDTH: 18PT; FONT-FAMILY: SYMBOL, SERIF; FONT-SIZE: 10PT; VERTICAL-ALIGN: TOP; ALIGN: RIGHT">

</TD>
<TD STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; WIDTH: AUTO; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT; VERTICAL-ALIGN: TOP">
	Effect of any changes in concentration of credit.
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; MARGIN-LEFT: 18PT; FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
	A loan is generally considered impaired if it meets either of the following two criteria:
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY">
<TABLE STYLE="WIDTH: 100%; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT" ID="C0066E14A95C4AC29BD014025C69C7F2" CLASS="DSPFLISTTABLE" CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="0">
<TR>
<TD STYLE="WIDTH: 108PT">
</TD>
<TD STYLE="WIDTH: 18PT; FONT-FAMILY: SYMBOL, SERIF; FONT-SIZE: 10PT; VERTICAL-ALIGN: TOP; ALIGN: RIGHT">
	&#183;
</TD>
<TD STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; WIDTH: AUTO; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT; VERTICAL-ALIGN: TOP">
	Loans that are 90 days or more in arrears (nonaccrual loans); or
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY">
<TABLE STYLE="WIDTH: 100%; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT" ID="A7E98EC060F44778AE6CCA8BDBE17BEA" CLASS="DSPFLISTTABLE" CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="0">
<TR>
<TD STYLE="WIDTH: 108PT">
</TD>
<TD STYLE="WIDTH: 18PT; FONT-FAMILY: SYMBOL, SERIF; FONT-SIZE: 10PT; VERTICAL-ALIGN: TOP; ALIGN: RIGHT">
	&#183;
</TD>
<TD STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; WIDTH: AUTO; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT; VERTICAL-ALIGN: TOP">
	Loans where, based on current information and events, it is probable that a borrower will be unable to pay all amounts due according to the contractual terms of the loan agreement.
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; TEXT-INDENT: 18PT; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
	Credit quality risk ratings include regulatory classifications of special mention, substandard, doubtful and loss.&#160; Loans, classified special mention have potential weaknesses that deserve management&#8217;s close attention.&#160; If uncorrected, the potential weaknesses may result in deterioration of the repayment prospects.&#160; Loans classified substandard have a well-defined weakness or weaknesses that jeopardize the liquidation of the debt.&#160; They include loans that are inadequately protected by the current sound net worth and paying capacity of the obligor or of the collateral pledged, if any.&#160; Loans classified doubtful have all the weaknesses inherent in loans classified substandard with the added characteristic that collection or liquidation in full, on the basis of current conditions and facts, is highly improbable.&#160; Loans classified as a loss are considered uncollectible and are charged to the allowance for loan losses.&#160; Loans not classified are rated pass.
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; TEXT-INDENT: 18PT; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
	A loan is considered a troubled debt restructuring, sometimes referred to as a TDR, when Bancorp for economic or legal reasons relating to the borrowers financial difficulties grants a concession to the borrower that it would not otherwise consider.&#160; Loan modifications made with terms consistent with current market conditions that the borrower could obtain in the open market are not considered a TDR.
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; TEXT-INDENT: 18PT; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
	Loans that experience insignificant payment delays and payment shortfalls generally are not classified as impaired.&#160; Management determines the significance of payment delays and payment shortfalls on a case-by-case basis, taking into consideration all of circumstances surrounding the loan and the borrower, including the length of the delay, the reasons for the delay, the borrower&#8217;s prior payment record, and the amount of the shortfall in relation to the principal and interest owed.
</DIV>
<DIV>
	&#160;
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="MARGIN-TOP: 10PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM: 10PT; CLEAR: BOTH" ID="DSPFPAGEBREAKAREA">
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: CENTER" ID="DSPFPAGENUMBERAREA">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-STYLE: NORMAL; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 8PT; FONT-WEIGHT: NORMAL" ID="DSPFPAGENUMBER">
	12
</FONT>
</DIV>

<DIV STYLE="WIDTH: 100%" ID="DSPFPAGEHEADER">
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: LEFT; FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL; FONT-STYLE: ITALIC; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 8PT; FONT-WEIGHT: NORMAL">

	Table of Contents
</A>
</DIV>
</DIV>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; TEXT-INDENT: 18PT; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
	The Bank discontinues the accrual of interest on loans 90 days or more past due, at which time all previously accrued but uncollected interest is deducted from income.&#160; $585,000 in interest income would have been recorded for the year ended December 31, 2015 if the loans had been current in accordance with their original terms and had been outstanding throughout the year ended December 31, 2015 or since their origination (if held for only part of the fiscal year).&#160; For the year ended December 31, 2015, $455,000 in interest income on such loans was actually included in net income.&#160; The following table sets forth information as to non-accrual loans and other non-performing assets.
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>
<EFX_UNIDENTIFIED_TABLE>
<A NAME="FIS_UNIDENTIFIED_TABLE_9"></A>
<TABLE STYLE="WIDTH: 100%; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT" ID="DC5CDC07BC8D45D5A1C27E1DFBB77E33" CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="0">

	Included in non-accrual residential mortgage loans at December 31, 2015, were seventeen loans totaling $2,891,000 to consumers and two loans totaling $300,000 to builders.&#160; Included in non-accrual land loans at December 31, 2015 were three loans totaling $277,000.

</FONT>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="PAGE-BREAK-AFTER: ALWAYS" ID="DSPFPAGEBREAK">
<HR STYLE="BORDER-RIGHT-WIDTH: 0PX; BACKGROUND-COLOR: #000000; MARGIN: 4PX 0PX; WIDTH: 100%; BORDER-TOP-WIDTH: 0PX; BORDER-BOTTOM-WIDTH: 0PX; HEIGHT: 2PX; COLOR: #000000; CLEAR: BOTH; BORDER-LEFT-WIDTH: 0PX" NOSHADE="NOSHADE">
</DIV>
<A NAME="eolPage19"></A>
<DIV STYLE="WIDTH: 100%" ID="DSPFPAGEHEADER">
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: LEFT; FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL; FONT-STYLE: ITALIC; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 8PT; FONT-WEIGHT: NORMAL">

	Table of Contents
</A>
</DIV>
</DIV>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-WEIGHT: BOLD">
	Classified Assets
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; TEXT-INDENT: 18PT; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
	Federal regulations provide for the classification of loans and other assets, such as debt and equity securities, considered by the OCC to be of lesser quality, as &#8220;substandard,&#8221; &#8220;doubtful&#8221; or &#8220;loss assets.&#8221; An asset is considered substandard if the paying capacity and net worth of the obligor or the collateral pledged, if any, inadequately protects it.&#160; Substandard assets include those characterized by the distinct possibility that the insured institution will sustain some loss if the deficiencies are not corrected.&#160; Assets classified as doubtful have all of the weaknesses inherent in those classified substandard with the added characteristic that the weaknesses present make collection or liquidation in full highly questionable and improbable, on the basis of currently existing facts, conditions, and values.&#160; Assets classified as loss assets are those considered uncollectible and of such little value that their continuance as assets without the establishment of a specific loss reserve is not warranted.&#160; Assets that do not currently expose the insured institution to a sufficient degree of risk to warrant classification in one of these categories but possess credit deficiencies or potential weakness are required to be designated special mention by management.
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; TEXT-INDENT: 18PT; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
	When an insured institution classifies problem assets as either substandard or doubtful, it is required to establish general allowances for losses in an amount deemed prudent by management.&#160; General allowances represent loss allowances which have been established to recognize the inherent risk associated with lending activities, but which, unlike specific allowances, have not been allocated to particular problem assets.&#160; When an insured institution classifies problem assets as loss assets, it is to charge-off such amount.&#160; An institution&#8217;s determination as to the classification of its assets is subject to scrutiny by the OCC, which can require the establishment of additional general or specific loss allowances.&#160; The Bank reviews monthly the assets in its portfolio to determine whether any assets require classification in accordance with applicable regulations.
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; TEXT-INDENT: 18PT; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
	Total classified loans decreased $13,988,000 to $13,873,000 at December 31, 2015 from $27,861,000 at December 31, 2014 primarily due to an improving economy.&#160; All of these loans were classified as substandard.&#160;&#160; The allowance for loan losses as of December 31, 2015 was $8,758,000, which was 1.4% of gross loans receivable and 97.6% of total non-performing loans.
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: CENTER; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT">

<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-WEIGHT: BOLD">
<U>
	Investment Activities
</U>
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; TEXT-INDENT: 18PT; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
	Federal thrift institutions, such as the Bank, have authority to invest in various types of liquid assets, including United States Treasury obligations and securities of various federal agencies, certificates of deposit at insured banks, bankers' acceptances and federal funds.&#160; As a member of the FHLB System, the Bank must maintain minimum levels of liquid assets specified by the OCC, which vary from time to time.&#160; Subject to various regulatory restrictions, federal thrift institutions may also invest a portion of their assets in certain commercial paper, corporate debt securities and mutual funds whose assets conform to the investments that a federal thrift institution is authorized to make directly.
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; MARGIN-LEFT: 18PT; FONT-SIZE: 10PT">

</DIV>

<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-WEIGHT: BOLD">
<U>
	Deposits
</U>
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; TEXT-INDENT: 18PT; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
	Deposits are attracted principally from within the Bank&#8217;s primary market areas through the offering of a variety of deposit instruments, including passbook and statement accounts and certificates of deposit ranging in terms from three months to five years.&#160; Deposit account terms vary, principally on the basis of the minimum balance required; the time periods the funds must remain on deposit and the interest rate.&#160; The Bank also offers individual retirement accounts.
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; TEXT-INDENT: 18PT; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
	The Bank&#8217;s policies are designed primarily to attract deposits from local residents rather than to solicit deposits from areas outside the Bank&#8217;s primary markets.&#160; Interest rates paid, maturity terms, service fees and withdrawal penalties are established by the Bank on a periodic basis.&#160; Determination of rates and terms are predicated upon funds acquisition and liquidity requirements, rates paid by competitors, growth goals and federal regulations.
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; MARGIN-LEFT: 18PT; FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
	Deposits in the Bank as of December 31, 2015, 2014 and 2013 consisted of savings programs described below:
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>

<DIV STYLE="WIDTH: 100%" ID="DSPFPAGEHEADER">
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: LEFT; FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL; FONT-STYLE: ITALIC; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 8PT; FONT-WEIGHT: NORMAL">

	Table of Contents

</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: LEFT; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-WEIGHT: BOLD">
<U>
	Liquidity and Asset/Liability Management
</U>
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; TEXT-INDENT: 18PT; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
	Two major objectives of asset and liability management are to maintain adequate liquidity and to control the interest sensitivity of the balance sheet.
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; TEXT-INDENT: 18PT; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
	Liquidity is the measure of a company&#8217;s ability to maintain sufficient cash flow to fund operations and to meet financial obligations to depositors and borrowers.&#160; Liquidity is provided by the ability to attract and retain deposits and by principal and interest payments on loans and maturing securities in the investment portfolio.&#160; A strong core deposit base, supplemented by other deposits of varying maturities and rates, contributes to the Bank&#8217;s liquidity.
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; TEXT-INDENT: 18PT; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
	Management believes that funds available through short-term borrowings and asset maturities are adequate to meet all anticipated needs for the next twelve months, and management is continually monitoring the Bank&#8217;s liquidity position to meet projected needs.
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; TEXT-INDENT: 18PT; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
	Interest rate sensitivity is maintaining the ability to reprice interest earning assets and interest bearing liabilities in relationship to changes in the general level of interest rates.&#160; Management attributes interest rate sensitivity to a steady net interest margin through all phases of interest rate cycles.&#160; Management attempts to make the necessary adjustments to constrain adverse swings in net interest income resulting from interest rate movements through gap analysis and income simulation modeling techniques.
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-WEIGHT: BOLD">
<U>
	Borrowings
</U>
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; TEXT-INDENT: 18PT; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
	The Bank&#8217;s credit availability under the FHLB of Atlanta&#8217;s credit availability program was $192,672,000 at December 31, 2015.&#160; The Bank&#8217;s credit availability is based on the level of collateral pledged up to 25% of total assets. The Bank, from time to time, utilizes the line of credit when interest rates under the line are more favorable than obtaining deposits from the public.&#160; There were no short-term borrowings with the FHLB of Atlanta at December 31, 2015.
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-WEIGHT: BOLD">

<BR>

<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; TEXT-INDENT: 18PT; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
	As of December 31, 2015, Bancorp and its subsidiaries had approximately 152 full-time equivalent employees.&#160; &#160; Bancorp&#8217;s employees are not represented by any collective bargaining group.
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-WEIGHT: BOLD">

</U>

	Hyatt Commercial is a subsidiary of the bank and is a real estate brokerage company specializing in commercial real estate sales, leasing and property management.
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-WEIGHT: BOLD">

	SBI Mortgage Company
</U>
</DIV>

<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; TEXT-INDENT: 18PT; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
	SBI Mortgage Company (&#8220;SBI&#8221;) is a subsidiary of Bancorp that has engaged in the origination of mortgages not suitable for the Bank.&#160; It owns subsidiary companies that purchase real estate for investment purposes.&#160; As of December 31, 2015, SBI had $1,444,000 in outstanding mortgage loans and it had $479,000 invested in subsidiaries, which funds were held in cash, pending potential acquisition of investment real estate.
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>

<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: LEFT; FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL; FONT-STYLE: ITALIC; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 8PT; FONT-WEIGHT: NORMAL">

<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: LEFT; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-WEIGHT: BOLD">
<U>
	HS West, LLC
</U>
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: JUSTIFY; TEXT-INDENT: 21.6PT; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
	HS West, LLC (&#8220;HS&#8221;) is a subsidiary of the Bank, and constructed a building in Annapolis, Maryland that serves as Bancorp&#8217;s and the Bank&#8217;s administrative headquarters. A branch office of the Bank is also located in the building.&#160; In addition, HS leases space to four unrelated companies and to a law firm of which the President of Bancorp and the Bank is a partner.
</DIV>
<DIV>
<BR>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN: LEFT; FONT-FAMILY: 'TIMES NEW ROMAN'; FONT-SIZE: 10PT; FONT-WEIGHT: BOLD">
